value.value: A vertebral arch that is part of the first cervical vertebra.
An anatomical structure that is regional part of the central nervous system where there is a significant bend of the axis.
A sharp, ventrally concave bend in the developing midbrain of the embryo[MP].
A ventrally concave flexure of the embryonic brain occurring at the junction of hindbrain and spinal cord[MP].

A dorsally concave bend of the embryonic rhombencephalon that produces a thinning of the roof of the pons and medulla oblongata and defines the boundary between the metencephalon and myelencephalon in the embryo[MP].
A fascicle that is part of a spinal cord.
A fascicle that is part of a brain.
A spinal cord segment that adjacent_to a sacral region.
A spinal cord segment that adjacent_to a caudal region.

definition.value: for spinal cord segments, we treat coccygeal/caudal as synonyms - we only differentiate where bone is concerned

value.value: A subdivision of spinal cord ventral column that is part of a thoracic spinal cord.
A subdivision of spinal cord ventral column that is part of a sacral spinal cord.
A subdivision of spinal cord ventral column that is part of a cervical spinal cord.
A subdivision of spinal cord ventral column that is part of a lumbar spinal cord.
A delimited region of dense mesenchyme within looser mesenchyme.
Cell condensation that is an aggregation of mesenchymal cells that are committed to differentiate into chondroblasts and chondrocytes.
A delimited region of dense mesenchyme within looser mesenchyme whose cells are committed to become chondroblasts.
The paired ventral prominences formed by bifurcation of the first pharyngeal arches in the embryo; the two prominences unite ventrally and fuse to form the mandible and lower lip.
The paired dorsal prominences formed by bifurcation of the first pharyngeal arches in the embryo that unite with the ipsilateral medial nasal process to form the upper jaw.
An indentation of the olfactory placode which ends when the pits hollows out to form the nasopharynx[GO].
A thick, horizontal process of the maxilla. It forms the anterior three quarters of the hard palate, the horizontal plate of the palatine bone making up the rest.
A groove that is situated between the 1st and 2nd pharyngeal arch.
A groove that is situated between the 2nd and 3rd pharyngeal arch.
A groove that is situated between the 3rd and 4th pharyngeal arch.
A groove that is situated between the 4th and 5th pharyngeal arch.

The embryonic anlage of the external genitalia, which emerges as paired swellings ventral to the cloacal membrane, is proposed to be derived from all three germ layers, and gives rise to the penis, clitoris, scrotum, labia, and foreskin.
An external pocketing of pharyngeal ectoderm that contacts a region of endoderm (a pharyngeal pouch) and interdigitates in the anterior and posterior directions by the pharyngeal arches.
A subdivision of the autopod that corresponds to one or more bones arranged in series branching from the main limb axis.

definition.value: encompasses digits and prepollex. requires review

value.value: The mantle layer of the neural tube that lies dorsal to the sulcus limitans and contains primarily sensory neurons and interneurons involved in communication of sensory impulses.
A subdivision of skeleton that supports pharyngeal arch 2.
The epithelial lining of the surface of the coelom.
A bone that is part of the region of the hindlimb that includes the zeugopod and stylopod. Examples: patella, femur, tibia. Counter-examples: any pes phalanx.
A bone that is part of the manus skeleton. Note that this includes the carpal bones.
A bone that is part of the pes skeleton.
Anatomical cluster that is located in the posterior region of the cranium and forms the margin of the foramen magnum and occipital condyles.

Each seminal vesicle consists of a single tube, coiled upon itself, and giving off several irregular cecal diverticula; the separate coils, as well as the diverticula, are connected together by fibrous tissue. When uncoiled, the tube is about the diameter of a quill, and varies in length from 10 to 15 cm.; it ends posteriorly in a cul-de-sac; its anterior extremity becomes constricted into a narrow straight duct called the excretory duct of seminal gland (or duct of the seminal vesicle), which joins with the corresponding ductus deferens to form the ejaculatory duct[WP].
Any of the ducts that are part of a male reproductive system.
Organ with organ cavity, which has as parts a serous membrane and a serous cavity . Examples: pleural sac, pericardial sac, tendon sheath, bursa.[FMA].
A serous sac which is the aggregate of the conjunctiva plus the conjunctival space.
Epithelium that derives from the endoderm. Examples: urothelium, transitional epithelium of ureter, epithelium of prostatic gland.[FMA].
A naris that provides one of the small external openings of the head that give passage to air for breathing.
Thickening of the proximal end of the hair follicle. Contains rapidly proliferating, rather undifferentiated matrix cells (transient amplifying cells), melanocytes and outer root sheath cells.

A multilayered tube composed of terminally differentiated hair follicle keratinocytes that is surrounded by the outer root sheath; the layers of the inner root sheath include the companion layer, Henle's layer, Huxley's layer and the inner root sheath cuticle[MP].
A stratified epithelium that surrounds the hair follicle that merges proximally with the basal layer of the interfollicular epidermis and distally with the hair bulb.
Subdivision of skeleton which consists of cranial skeleton, set of all vertebrae, set of all ribs and sternum[FMA, modified].
